14:11.500 --> 14:14.460
You brought a baseless,
frivolous cause of acion

14:14.500 --> 14:16.600
barred by law.
Why?

14:18.700 --> 14:20.000
Are you done?

14:20.500 --> 14:23.140
Go ahead. Let me have it.
I'm a big boy.

14:26.800 --> 14:29.860
I've practiced a long time,
worked with some of

14:29.900 --> 14:31.760
the highest-ranking members
of our profession—

14:31.800 --> 14:33.500
I include you among them—

14:33.800 --> 14:35.560
But I have yet
to be associated

14:35.600 --> 14:39.600
with a more skilled,
more principled,

14:40.100 --> 14:43.100
more noble attorney
than Alan Shore.

14:44.200 --> 14:46.960
If his is the reputation
I'm to be saddled with,

14:47.000 --> 14:51.000
I will take it.
And lunch is over.

14:53.100 --> 14:54.760
If you want to reject
my opinion,

14:54.800 --> 14:56.700
that's your prerogative.

14:56.700 --> 15:01.000
But here's a fact:
he is putting your firm in peril.

15:01.800 --> 15:03.912
Believe me
when I tell you that.

15:20.000 --> 15:21.760
Jerry, thank you so much
for helping me tell him.

15:21.800 --> 15:23.560
I'm just so afraid
if he hears it from me,

15:23.600 --> 15:25.400
he'll hate my guts forever.

15:25.500 --> 15:27.400
Hey, mom.
Hi, uncle Jerry.

15:27.600 --> 15:29.700
Henry! Hello. Welcome.

15:32.400 --> 15:33.984
This could take a while.

15:35.100 --> 15:36.260
It's so good
to see you.

15:36.300 --> 15:39.000
You, too.
This is my girlfriend Fiona.

15:39.000 --> 15:40.260
I brought her along,
if that's okay.

15:40.300 --> 15:42.100
We're kind of inseparable.

15:47.800 --> 15:50.360
So what's the big mystery? Did I
inherit money or something?

15:50.400 --> 15:51.360
Did my birth father keel?

15:51.400 --> 15:52.500
Henry.

15:53.200 --> 15:54.982
So really,
what's the deal?

15:57.000 --> 16:00.700
Let's… go into the conference
room where we all can sit.

16:08.000 --> 16:10.260
Are you currently serving
in the military, sir?

16:10.300 --> 16:13.072
No, I'm a retired captain
for the US army.

16:13.200 --> 16:14.460
I served until last year.

16:14.500 --> 16:17.360
And what were your
primary responsibilities?

16:17.400 --> 16:20.360
For the last nine years,
I was mainly in recruiting,

16:20.400 --> 16:21.960
getting young men to enlist.

16:22.000 --> 16:23.760
Did you retire on good terms?

16:23.800 --> 16:24.900
Not so much.

16:24.900 --> 16:26.352
Could you tell us why?

16:26.500 --> 16:30.900
Well… it was suggested I retire
after I was a little too outspoken

16:30.900 --> 16:33.060
on what I perceived
as a backdoor draft.

16:33.100 --> 16:35.400
Um, when you say
“backdoor draft”—

16:35.400 --> 16:37.600
I mean we target the poor.

16:37.800 --> 16:40.260
No one likes to say it publicly,
but that's what we do.

16:40.300 --> 16:43.600
And you target
low-income youth because?

16:43.600 --> 16:45.460
They needed the money.
Most kids don't want

16:45.500 --> 16:47.860
to go off and fight wars
if they can avoid it,

16:47.900 --> 16:50.060
so we hone in on the kids
without options.

16:50.100 --> 16:51.100
The poor.

16:51.300 --> 16:54.060
The poor. We set up
our recruitment stations

16:54.100 --> 16:56.860
in the poor neighborhood malls
and in the poor high schools.

16:56.900 --> 16:58.200
I'm sorry.

16:58.200 --> 17:00.560
Can you at least tell me
the connection to this case?

17:00.600 --> 17:03.100
It goes to fairness,
Mr Mathis.

17:03.300 --> 17:05.660
We go after the lowest
economic demographic

17:05.700 --> 17:07.560
in our society
to fight our wars.

17:07.599 --> 17:11.260
These kids are risking their
lives out of financial duress.

17:11.300 --> 17:13.060
They have—
–I'm sorry, Ms Schmidt.

17:13.099 --> 17:15.900
This is an entirely
different issue.

17:16.200 --> 17:17.760
This witness is disallowed.

17:17.800 --> 17:20.260
Your honor, I would like you to
understand the context of this—

17:20.300 --> 17:22.060
No. We're gonna stay on issue.

17:22.099 --> 17:24.960
Now if you've got a witness
who can talk about this case

17:25.000 --> 17:27.260
or the doctrine itself,
I'll listen.

17:27.300 --> 17:30.600
Otherwise, this witness
is disallowed.

17:30.600 --> 17:32.300
Now who else do you have?

17:32.300 --> 17:34.260
Yes, I would like to hear
from the doctor

17:34.300 --> 17:35.960
who treated
my client's brother.

17:36.000 --> 17:38.960
Defense stipulated that he
committed an avoidable error

17:39.000 --> 17:41.310
rising to the level
of malpractice.

17:41.400 --> 17:42.860
I'd like to hear from him
all the same since—

17:42.900 --> 17:45.400
There's no point here
from the doctor

17:45.400 --> 17:47.260
unless you're trying
to manipulate me

17:47.300 --> 17:50.660
with either horror or emotion,
neither of which informs us

17:50.700 --> 17:52.000
of the legitimacy

17:52.000 --> 17:55.000
or the lawfulness
of the Feres doctrine.

17:55.000 --> 17:57.260
Your honor, certainly you're
allowed to be horrified

17:57.300 --> 17:58.360
by the facts in this case.

17:58.400 --> 18:00.800
The doctor is disallowed.

18:00.800 --> 18:03.460
In order to fully appreciate
this doctrine

18:03.500 --> 18:05.360
and its capricious
application,

18:05.400 --> 18:06.660
your honor needs to hear test—

18:06.700 --> 18:07.560
Oh, wait a minute.

18:07.600 --> 18:10.260
You've—you've wasted
enough of my time already.

18:10.300 --> 18:13.100
I'd like to hear summations
from counsel

18:13.100 --> 18:15.600
in this court
tomorrow at 10:00 am,

18:15.600 --> 18:17.100
and then I'll rule.

18:17.300 --> 18:20.996
In the meantime, I'd like to see
counsel in my chambers.

18:25.200 --> 18:26.000
Well…

18:27.100 --> 18:29.900
It, um, uh, might be… best

18:29.900 --> 18:33.100
if this conversation were—
were private.

18:33.100 --> 18:35.760
Mom, whatever it is,
I'm gonna tell Fiona.

18:35.800 --> 18:37.054
She's my soul mate.

18:37.800 --> 18:38.800
Okay.

18:40.000 --> 18:40.700
Well…

18:42.700 --> 18:44.100
The thing is, Henry…

18:48.000 --> 18:48.600
Tell him.

18:50.900 --> 18:52.900
Well, Henry, hello.
Welcome.

18:52.900 --> 18:56.060
This is a little bit about
your birth father, actually.

18:56.100 --> 18:57.560
–Did he croak?
–No. No, no, no.

18:57.600 --> 18:59.360
Well, we have no way of knowing
one way or another

18:59.400 --> 19:01.360
since we have no idea
who he even is.

19:01.400 --> 19:03.060
Fiona's a sperm-donor baby too.

19:03.100 --> 19:05.160
It's one of the first things
we bonded over.

19:05.200 --> 19:09.200
Yes, in fact, you're not
just sperm-donor babies.

19:09.200 --> 19:13.800
But you both come from
the same sperm bank, actually.

19:13.800 --> 19:14.600
Really?

19:15.600 --> 19:19.200
Cool. You see?
We're so much alike.

19:19.200 --> 19:20.960
M-more alike
than you might imagine.

19:21.000 --> 19:26.300
It's possible… you came
from the same sperm donor.

19:27.500 --> 19:28.360
What do you mean?

19:28.400 --> 19:29.400
Well…

19:30.600 --> 19:33.600
You may have…

19:36.400 --> 19:37.300
Um…

19:39.400 --> 19:41.500
The same birth father.

19:42.300 --> 19:43.660
The odds are against it,
of course,

19:43.700 --> 19:46.700
but there's a wee chance that…

19:49.100 --> 19:50.800
uh, Fiona…

19:51.800 --> 19:52.900
is…

19:55.400 --> 19:57.600
your half sister.

20:00.800 --> 20:02.500
That—it can't be.

20:02.500 --> 20:06.200
I-I—I'm sure it isn't,
but, uh, um, it might be.

20:08.500 --> 20:11.900
How can we know… for sure?

20:11.900 --> 20:15.100
Well… that's the thing.

20:15.100 --> 20:18.100
Uh, we… can't.

20:18.100 --> 20:20.900
We're trying, but so far…

20:22.000 --> 20:23.500
We can't.

20:32.000 --> 20:35.800
I have been informed…

20:35.800 --> 20:39.800
that counsel has been
wagering on this case.

20:39.900 --> 20:41.200
Is that true?

20:43.400 --> 20:45.400
That is absolutely false.

20:45.400 --> 20:47.800
Mr Shore…

20:47.800 --> 20:49.600
What about you?
–Me?

20:49.600 --> 20:50.260
I've been informed

20:50.300 --> 20:55.400
that you and Denny Crane
have a side bet for $50,000.

20:55.400 --> 20:56.700
Is that true?

20:59.200 --> 21:01.700
–Well…
–Alan?

21:04.800 --> 21:06.516
Proceeds go to the troops.

21:07.400 --> 21:09.160
I never bet on baseball,
and I bet we'd win here,

21:09.200 --> 21:11.360
so it's not as if
I'm throwing anything here.

21:11.400 --> 21:14.700
But a senior partner
in your firm—

21:14.700 --> 21:17.560
Denny and I have these
little side bets all the time.

21:17.600 --> 21:21.600
It's not like…
that answer remotely helped me.

21:22.100 --> 21:23.460
I lied about that actually.

21:23.500 --> 21:25.760
Denny and I don't bet all the time.

21:25.800 --> 21:29.400
I never bet. I just… lie.

21:29.400 --> 21:32.766
My therapist recommends
that I lie to get past the…

21:34.100 --> 21:35.060
gambling problem.

21:35.100 --> 21:37.360
Well, I'm recommending you for disbarment

21:37.400 --> 21:39.360
as soon as this case is through.

21:39.400 --> 21:43.200
All right. Summation,
10:00 am tomorrow.

22:01.500 --> 22:03.600
–You told the judge?
–What?

22:03.600 --> 22:05.160
About our bet. You told the judge.

22:05.200 --> 22:07.000
I did no such thing.

22:07.000 --> 22:08.360
Well, he knows, Denny.
How would he know?

22:08.400 --> 22:09.160
Don't ask me.

22:09.200 --> 22:11.460
You never said anything to anybody?

22:11.500 --> 22:14.960
Well, I-I might have mentioned
it to the clerk in passing.

22:15.000 --> 22:17.300
–I don't believe it.
–Calm down.

22:17.300 --> 22:19.700
You sabotaged a case of this firm

22:19.700 --> 22:22.260
so you could win a bet?
You sabotaged me.

22:22.300 --> 22:25.060
–Keep your voice down.
–I will not keep my voice down.

22:25.100 --> 22:27.060
You sold me out.
I'm up for disbarment now.

22:27.100 --> 22:28.660
You might be, too.
–I'll make a few calls.

22:28.700 --> 22:30.900
Denny, we wagered on a case.

22:30.900 --> 22:34.000
Do you have any idea
how unethical that is?

22:34.000 --> 22:36.060
Well, it's not like
we bet on baseball.

22:36.100 --> 22:39.200
You did this to me,
to your best friend.

22:39.200 --> 22:43.200
Winning a bet is… My God.

22:48.600 --> 22:49.460
She looks mad.

22:49.500 --> 22:51.900
Of all the things
you have done…

22:51.900 --> 22:54.300
never mind the illegality of it,

22:54.300 --> 22:56.400
the insensitivity…

22:56.400 --> 22:58.500
A soldier lost his life.

22:58.500 --> 23:01.100
–Shirley—
–There is no excuse, Alan.

23:01.100 --> 23:03.100
I wasn't about to offer any.

23:03.100 --> 23:04.760
It was stupid.
We never should have done it.

23:04.800 --> 23:07.660
If I thought it would have any
bearing on the case, I never w—

23:07.700 --> 23:09.500
Of course it has bearing.

23:09.500 --> 23:12.160
The judge now takes our case
much less seriously bec—

23:12.200 --> 23:13.560
Which was obviously Denny's plan,

23:13.600 --> 23:14.560
which is why he told the clerk.

23:14.600 --> 23:16.100
Oh, sure. Sell me out.

23:16.100 --> 23:18.900
You sold me out.
You betrayed me.

23:18.900 --> 23:21.500
You both betrayed me…

23:21.500 --> 23:24.000
and this firm and the client.

23:27.800 --> 23:30.600
You sicken me, both of you.

23:35.800 --> 23:37.160
Maybe I shouldn't have told.

23:37.200 --> 23:38.700
Maybe⁈

23:40.100 --> 23:42.100
You risked everything.

23:42.100 --> 23:46.100
Our friendship, our trust,
our nights on the balcony—

23:46.600 --> 23:48.860
You put a stupid bet before it all.

23:48.900 --> 23:50.360
I mean—you know what?
I don't care.

23:50.400 --> 23:53.000
I'm done. We're done.

23:54.100 --> 23:56.400
–Alan.
–I can't even look at you.

24:03.800 --> 24:06.560
So this isn't any kind of
in vitro facility or—

24:06.600 --> 24:08.160
No, your honor.
It's simply a bank.

24:08.200 --> 24:09.660
People buy and sell sperm.

24:09.700 --> 24:11.560
And do people buy and sell
a lot of it,

24:11.600 --> 24:14.960
or has the weakened American dollar
taken its toll there as well?

24:15.000 --> 24:17.860
Your honor, I certainly hope
you're not finding humor in this.

24:17.900 --> 24:20.260
The consequences here
are potentially dire.

24:20.300 --> 24:23.560
Look, the odds of two people from
the same donor meeting are—

24:23.600 --> 24:25.000
Not preposterous.

24:25.000 --> 24:27.460
Many donors donate buckets
of sperm over time.

24:27.500 --> 24:30.260
In fact, with designer babies
and genetic engineering

24:30.300 --> 24:32.660
being the new must-have
for wealthy families,

24:32.700 --> 24:34.560
many prospective parents
go looking for

24:34.600 --> 24:37.960
that athletic good-looking man
with the ivy league degree.

24:38.000 --> 24:39.160
There are some donors

24:39.200 --> 24:43.100
who have sired more offspring
than secretariat.

24:43.100 --> 24:44.560
It's only a matter of time

24:44.600 --> 24:48.000
before two people from
the same seed hook up.

24:48.000 --> 24:50.560
Crown cryobank follows
the guidelines recommended by

24:50.600 --> 24:52.960
the American society
for reproductive medicine

24:53.000 --> 24:56.160
to specifically guard against
the possibility of consanguinity.

24:56.200 --> 24:57.500
But it can happen.

24:57.500 --> 25:00.360
Looking at these two kids,
you can see the possibility.

25:00.400 --> 25:01.560
Your honor, if I may,

25:01.600 --> 25:03.960
we limit the number of
live births per donor

25:04.000 --> 25:07.400
to 25 per population of 800,000.

25:07.400 --> 25:09.960
But you have no means of
actually tracking that number.

25:10.000 --> 25:12.060
There's no obligation
for the women to tell you

25:12.100 --> 25:14.460
the resultslt of the purchased
sperm once it leaves the depot.

25:14.500 --> 25:16.960
We have binding contracts
with our donors.

25:17.000 --> 25:19.260
But if you talked to adopted children,

25:19.300 --> 25:21.610
they will tell you there is a need.

25:22.100 --> 25:25.260
Even the—the ones raised
by loving adoptive families,

25:25.300 --> 25:27.800
there is a fundamental,

25:27.800 --> 25:29.900
perhaps even primal need,

25:29.900 --> 25:33.200
to know who and where they came from.

25:33.200 --> 25:35.500
And these contracts say,

25:35.500 --> 25:38.900
“no, sorry, sperm donors'
privacy counts more.”

25:38.900 --> 25:40.100
That's wrong.

25:40.100 --> 25:42.460
Parents have always treated
children like chattel,

25:42.500 --> 25:44.160
like acquisitions, but this…

25:44.200 --> 25:45.900
The UK passed a law

25:45.900 --> 25:48.660
ending the practice of
donating sperm anonymously.

25:48.700 --> 25:50.960
Fertility clinics started to dry up.

25:51.000 --> 25:52.560
Some have no sperm at all.

25:52.600 --> 25:54.382
Desperate parents lose out.

25:55.100 --> 25:56.300
All right.

25:56.300 --> 25:58.214
I think I know the arguments.

25:59.600 --> 26:00.900
Yes, son?

26:02.400 --> 26:04.200
I just want to say, judge,

26:04.200 --> 26:06.400
nobody ever consulted me.

26:06.400 --> 26:07.660
Now if I want to know
where I came from,

26:07.700 --> 26:09.400
who my birth father is,

26:09.400 --> 26:11.060
does cancer run in the family,

26:11.100 --> 26:13.960
are there any other diseases
I might be more likely to get,

26:14.000 --> 26:16.060
do I have any brothers or sisters,

26:16.100 --> 26:19.400
is there anybody else out there
who looks like me—

26:19.800 --> 26:22.000
I don't get to know any of that…

26:22.000 --> 26:26.158
because before I was born,
some people entered into a contract.

26:43.400 --> 26:44.600
I'm sorry.

26:45.100 --> 26:48.860
Go tell someone who's interested.
I'm working on my summation.

26:48.900 --> 26:50.700
–Alan, I—
–Get out.

26:50.700 --> 26:52.548
You don't do something like…

26:53.600 --> 26:55.400
Sorry isn't good enough.

27:03.000 --> 27:04.400
Alan…

27:05.700 --> 27:07.000
I'm slipping.

27:09.600 --> 27:12.200
What would ever…

27:13.100 --> 27:14.800
possess me to—

27:14.800 --> 27:16.360
I mean, I do crazy things,

27:16.400 --> 27:19.900
but I-I always know what I'm doing.

27:20.600 --> 27:22.300
My judgment on this was…

27:28.600 --> 27:30.200
I know I'm slipping.

27:33.200 --> 27:34.800
I'm so, so sorry.

27:34.800 --> 27:39.300
For me to have done this to
the person I love most is…

27:41.300 --> 27:43.100
What's happening to me?

27:43.800 --> 27:45.460
Nothing's happening to you.

27:45.500 --> 27:47.100
Yes, it is.

27:47.100 --> 27:48.400
I'm not sure.

27:48.400 --> 27:50.710
Maybe I shouldn't practice anymore.

27:51.300 --> 27:52.900
Look, don't overreact.

27:52.900 --> 27:55.700
I told the clerk of a sitting judge

27:55.700 --> 27:57.900
we had a bet on the case.

28:01.900 --> 28:05.400
If I'm going down, I—I'm not
taking you down with me.

28:05.900 --> 28:07.200
It's time I quit.

28:07.800 --> 28:09.160
If you quit work, Denny,

28:09.200 --> 28:12.360
your brain will shrivel up
to the size of a small raisin,

28:12.400 --> 28:14.300
and you surely will die.

28:20.400 --> 28:24.000
Have you been feeling
other symptoms lately?

28:25.100 --> 28:27.400
Sometimes I feel a little foggy

28:27.400 --> 28:30.800
and I don't seem to always get things.

28:30.800 --> 28:32.700
–For example?
–Obama.

28:32.700 --> 28:33.360
Another example.

28:33.400 --> 28:35.800
The Patriots losing to the Giants.

28:36.500 --> 28:38.400
You're covering.

28:43.800 --> 28:44.960
The idea of not having you—

28:45.000 --> 28:47.300
You will never not have me.

28:49.700 --> 28:51.200
You said we were done.

28:51.200 --> 28:53.500
I was angry, Denny.

28:53.500 --> 28:55.200
I'll get by it.

28:56.100 --> 29:01.400
Our friendship will survive
an act of poor judgment.

29:02.500 --> 29:04.900
–Really?
–Really.

29:16.000 --> 29:17.160
If you want to call off the bet—

29:17.200 --> 29:18.860
I have no interest in doing that.

29:18.900 --> 29:20.000
I plan on winng.

29:22.000 --> 29:24.100
–Double it?
–Done.

29:25.800 --> 29:27.100
Don't tell.

29:27.100 --> 29:27.900
I won't.

29:28.900 --> 29:30.100
Thank you, Alan.

29:31.100 --> 29:34.400
You forgive, I forget—
We make a good team.

29:34.400 --> 29:37.900
Yes. We're a very good team.

29:54.800 --> 29:55.600
All right.

29:56.800 --> 29:58.800
Look, when I grew up,

29:58.800 --> 30:02.360
it was relatively rare to meet
a person who was adopted.

30:02.400 --> 30:04.900
Today adoption is commonplace,

30:04.900 --> 30:07.500
as are multicultural families.

30:07.500 --> 30:12.000
Genealogy is almost considered irrelevant.

30:12.000 --> 30:13.160
But it is relevant.

30:13.200 --> 30:15.860
People do want to know
their genetic history,

30:15.900 --> 30:17.660
whether it is for medical reasons

30:17.700 --> 30:21.100
or just, well, to feel complete

30:21.100 --> 30:23.900
as one adopted friend recently told me.

30:23.900 --> 30:26.000
I agree with Mr Espenson.

30:26.000 --> 30:29.960
We cannot allow a contract
to usurp the autonomy of the child.

30:30.000 --> 30:32.260
The current laws are
anything but current,

30:32.300 --> 30:34.346
and they need to be reexamined.

30:34.700 --> 30:38.200
In the meantime,
I am not ordering the defendant

30:38.200 --> 30:41.960
to tell the plaintiff
the identity of his biological father.

30:42.000 --> 30:44.400
But I am ordering you to tell him

30:44.400 --> 30:46.700
if he and his girlfriend

30:46.700 --> 30:49.000
come from the same sperm donor.

30:50.100 --> 30:53.500
You have my ruling.
We are adjourned.

30:55.300 --> 30:56.620
So what happens now?

30:57.400 --> 30:59.660
Well, we at least find out
if you two are related.

30:59.700 --> 31:01.284
How long will that take?

31:01.600 --> 31:03.580
I would think we'd know today.

31:03.700 --> 31:07.400
Good work, Jerry.
I'm very impressed.

31:17.300 --> 31:21.360
It isn't just the undue economic burden
on the government, your honor,

31:21.400 --> 31:23.760
though that alone would be crippling.

31:23.800 --> 31:26.660
But the subject the military
hospitals to discovery?

31:26.700 --> 31:29.260
That could result in
the free trade of military secrets.

31:29.300 --> 31:32.400
It could compromise military discipline.

31:33.500 --> 31:34.860
Representative Duncan Hunter—

31:34.900 --> 31:37.160
a member of the house
armed services committee

31:37.200 --> 31:40.600
and a former fighter pilot—
consider what he said:

31:40.600 --> 31:43.560
“the Feres doctrine represents
a reasonable approach

31:43.600 --> 31:47.500
”to ensuring that litigation
does not interfere

31:47.500 --> 31:51.500
with the objectives and readiness
of our nation's military.”

31:51.500 --> 31:52.560
You know, and think of it?

31:52.600 --> 31:55.160
Do we really want our
military personnel bogged down

31:55.200 --> 31:59.800
in depositions and motions
while we're trying to fight a war?

31:59.800 --> 32:03.300
And finally, your honor…
consider this:

32:03.300 --> 32:07.200
military hospitals tend
to deal with high volume,

32:07.200 --> 32:10.700
and as Mr Shore noted,
many catastrophic wounds.

32:10.700 --> 32:13.060
We want these kids getting treatment.

32:13.100 --> 32:15.000
The last thing we need

32:15.000 --> 32:18.460
is for doctors to be balking
out of fear of getting sued.

32:18.500 --> 32:20.800
If you take away this immunity,

32:20.800 --> 32:23.400
the reality is,
you'll lose doctors,

32:23.400 --> 32:25.760
and our kids won't get
the medical treatment

32:25.800 --> 32:28.000
they've earned and deserve.

32:28.600 --> 32:29.660
Lawyers love to sue.

32:29.700 --> 32:31.860
It's what we do.
It's how we heat our pools.

32:31.900 --> 32:33.600
But sometimes…

32:34.400 --> 32:36.900
we have to put our country first.

32:36.900 --> 32:38.022
And failing that,

32:38.900 --> 32:41.210
how about you put our troops first?

32:48.900 --> 32:49.700
Ah.

32:50.800 --> 32:52.360
It's surprising to have to explain

32:52.400 --> 32:54.960
the rudiments of our legal system
to opposing counsel,

32:55.000 --> 32:56.800
but I am not suing anyone.

32:56.800 --> 32:59.760
My client is suing
because his brother, a soldier,

32:59.800 --> 33:02.500
was killed by a military hospital.

33:02.500 --> 33:04.860
By the way, there are
no pools being heated here.

33:04.900 --> 33:07.060
I don't have one,
and as for my client,

33:07.100 --> 33:09.760
he should be so lucky to have
a house, let alone a pool.

33:09.800 --> 33:12.460
Although I'm sure he'd
prefer to have his brother.

33:12.500 --> 33:15.760
Private Richard Canfield was in
the Fort Wayne military hospital

33:15.800 --> 33:19.260
getting basic follow-up treatment
for wounds sustained in Iraq,

33:19.300 --> 33:21.360
wounds he was healing from nicely.

33:21.400 --> 33:23.260
He began to have trouble breathing due to

33:23.300 --> 33:25.860
an adverse reaction to medicine
he was mistakenly given.

33:25.900 --> 33:28.960
The doctor then inserted
a breathing tube incorrectly

33:29.000 --> 33:31.060
and proceeded to pump air
into his stomach.

33:31.100 --> 33:33.760
By the time they figured out
their mistake 15 minutes later,

33:33.800 --> 33:36.060
private Canfield
had severe brain damage.

33:36.100 --> 33:37.900
Three days later, he died.

33:37.900 --> 33:39.360
None of this is in dispute.

33:39.400 --> 33:43.700
Had this same malpractice
happened to me or you,

33:43.700 --> 33:46.460
our estates would receive
million-dollar settlements.

33:46.500 --> 33:50.100
But because private Canfield
was a GI, not a nickel.

33:50.100 --> 33:52.700
Apparently, we can all live with that.

33:52.700 --> 33:58.400
This Feres doctrine is as unfair
as it is patently ludicrous.

33:58.400 --> 34:01.560
There is no danger of
revealing military secrets.

34:01.600 --> 34:03.960
Discovery would only go
to medical records.

34:04.000 --> 34:05.800
And frankly, I am mystified

34:05.800 --> 34:09.060
as to how this could possibly
affect military discipline.

34:09.100 --> 34:11.560
Would the troops
suddenly stop saluting

34:11.600 --> 34:14.699
or begin marching in crooked lines?

34:14.699 --> 34:17.460
And as for the supposed burden
on the government,

34:17.500 --> 34:18.960
you've gotta be kidding me.

34:19.000 --> 34:22.199
What about private Canfield's
horrific ordeal?

34:22.199 --> 34:24.060
Not to mention the obvious fact

34:24.100 --> 34:26.760
that while our government
will undoubtedly survive,

34:26.800 --> 34:29.100
private Canfield did not.

34:32.600 --> 34:33.960
I would say to you, your honor,

34:34.000 --> 34:36.178
these are our kids who are dying.

34:36.900 --> 34:40.199
But it's not really our kids, is it?

34:40.199 --> 34:41.699
Not for the most part.

34:42.600 --> 34:44.159
It's the poor people's kids.

34:44.199 --> 34:47.260
And the dirty little secret,
some might say windfall,

34:47.300 --> 34:49.960
of our record poverty
and disparity of wealth

34:50.000 --> 34:52.760
is that we've got plenty of poor people
with kids to fight our wars.

34:52.800 --> 34:54.460
I'm sorry, but I'm offended by that.

34:54.500 --> 34:55.360
Are you, really?

34:55.400 --> 34:57.160
How about a republican
presidential candidate

34:57.200 --> 34:59.660
who opposes educational benefits
for GIs

34:59.700 --> 35:01.960
so as not to encourage troops
to leave the military?

35:02.000 --> 35:04.260
Keep their options limited.
Does that offend you?

35:04.300 --> 35:06.860
How about all the war
profiteering by the rich?

35:06.900 --> 35:07.660
How about the fact

35:07.700 --> 35:11.660
that while an army sergeant gets
an annual salary of $70,000,

35:11.700 --> 35:14.760
private security guards hired
by Blackwater and Dyncorp

35:14.800 --> 35:16.360
get $400,000 to $500,000,

35:16.400 --> 35:17.260
does that offend you?

35:17.300 --> 35:21.060
All kinds of wonderful,
lucrative deals can happen in war,

35:21.100 --> 35:23.460
but for the GIs,
we've got the Feres doctrine,

35:23.500 --> 35:26.660
which means when a GI
is killed by hospital negligence

35:26.700 --> 35:29.660
or even deliberately
by a doctor, not a nickel.

35:29.700 --> 35:33.100
How can this not shock
our national conscience?

35:33.100 --> 35:35.060
The media gives it little if any shrift.

35:35.100 --> 35:36.760
Mr Mathis clearly doesn't care.

35:36.800 --> 35:39.836
And me? Hell, I even
placed a bet on the case.

35:44.800 --> 35:48.800
How can it be
that we don't… much care?

35:51.300 --> 35:54.336
Maybe because it's not
our kids who are dying.

35:55.200 --> 35:56.718
It's the poor people's.

36:15.400 --> 36:17.578
Yes. Yes, that's fine. I'll wait.

36:17.900 --> 36:18.900
I'm on hold.

36:20.700 --> 36:21.860
They have the answer?

36:21.900 --> 36:23.000
It seems so.

36:25.900 --> 36:27.352
It's going to be fine.

36:28.000 --> 36:29.700
I read a study.

36:29.700 --> 36:33.060
People are attracted to
other people who look like them.

36:33.100 --> 36:36.060
It's not unusual for us
to resemble each other.

36:36.100 --> 36:37.900
Yes. Thank you.

36:40.900 --> 36:41.800
Well?

36:50.800 --> 36:53.300
You have the same sperm donor.

37:00.700 --> 37:01.900
I'm sorry.

37:02.800 --> 37:04.300
This isn't fair.

37:09.000 --> 37:11.400
I'm so sorry.

37:34.900 --> 37:36.000
All rise.

37:38.800 --> 37:39.800
Be seated.

37:47.900 --> 37:50.160
I'm allowing the plaintiff's case to stand.

37:50.200 --> 37:52.960
Your honor, the precedent
set by the Feres doctrine—

37:53.000 --> 37:56.760
The Feres doctrine is no longer
applicable in today's world.

37:56.800 --> 37:58.660
Well, in that case,
the remedy is the legislature.

37:58.700 --> 38:00.300
I disagree, counselor.

38:00.300 --> 38:03.200
This doctrine unfairly victimizes the poor.

38:03.200 --> 38:07.800
There are far more rich people
registered to vote than poor people.

38:07.800 --> 38:11.460
This will never get fixed by
an electable legislature, never.

38:11.500 --> 38:14.160
–Your honor—
–I'm allowing the case to stand.

38:14.200 --> 38:16.200
We are adjourned.

38:18.600 --> 38:19.500
Well…

38:20.300 --> 38:21.160
What does this mean?

38:21.200 --> 38:22.960
It means for now, you still get to sue.

38:23.000 --> 38:25.310
Hopefully we can settle it quickly.

38:25.600 --> 38:26.300
Thank you.

38:26.300 --> 38:28.260
I'll schedule a meeting
with opposing counsel,

38:28.300 --> 38:29.460
and we'll see where it goes.

38:29.500 --> 38:30.900
I'll let you know.

38:35.000 --> 38:38.900
Shirley, I apologize again
for any embarrassment that—

38:43.600 --> 38:44.700
Okay.

38:52.900 --> 38:54.300
She'll forgive us.

38:55.200 --> 38:57.660
It sounds like
she's already halfway there.

38:57.700 --> 38:59.800
What makes you say that?

38:59.800 --> 39:03.260
Well, Shirley has no trouble
expressing her displeasure.

39:03.300 --> 39:07.100
But when she says nothing
or walks away in silence,

39:07.100 --> 39:08.800
it's like she's saying,

39:08.800 --> 39:12.600
“I'm still angry,
but I'll forgive you.”

39:17.000 --> 39:18.400
Will you…

39:18.400 --> 39:19.900
really forgive me?

39:20.900 --> 39:22.500
I did already.

39:27.800 --> 39:30.200
I can't believe

39:30.200 --> 39:32.900
I actually said that to the clerk.

39:32.900 --> 39:34.400
Promise me something—

39:34.400 --> 39:37.172
When I do something crazy,
you'll tell me.

39:38.500 --> 39:41.200
Okay, let's start
with doubling the bet.

39:42.200 --> 39:44.200
Oh, right. Yeah.

39:48.200 --> 39:51.260
At least tell me it's going
to a good cause, like a hooker.

39:51.300 --> 39:53.060
It's going to the troops. Remember?

39:53.100 --> 39:56.000
Oh, right, yes. I feel better now.

40:01.700 --> 40:03.100
You okay, Denny?

40:04.300 --> 40:05.400
Oh, yeah.

40:08.700 --> 40:10.284
You really yelled at me.

40:10.700 --> 40:12.300
I just lost my temper.

40:13.700 --> 40:15.000
I'm over it.

40:18.400 --> 40:20.314
You know what's long overdue?

40:20.900 --> 40:22.700
You and me on a road trip.

40:22.700 --> 40:24.400
A road trip.

40:24.400 --> 40:26.300
Maybe we should go to Rome,

40:26.300 --> 40:28.560
or the balcony on
the other side of the building.

40:28.600 --> 40:31.700
Yeah, I've got it.
A dude ranch.

40:31.700 --> 40:33.200
A dude ranch?

40:33.200 --> 40:38.200
It's horses and—and sheep
and fresh air and…

40:38.500 --> 40:39.600
Sheep.

40:40.800 --> 40:43.800
Let's go west,
to the wild west.

40:43.800 --> 40:45.800
I don't really like horses.

40:45.800 --> 40:47.700
How can you not like horses?

40:47.700 --> 40:48.800
Dude ranch?

40:48.800 --> 40:49.460
You just leave it to me.

40:49.500 --> 40:50.960
I'll make all the arrangements.

40:51.000 --> 40:54.900
We'll have campfires
and marshmallows and tents…

40:54.900 --> 40:55.900
and… sheep.

40:56.500 --> 40:58.000
Me and you and…

40:58.900 --> 41:01.012
Fresh air would do us both good.

41:01.500 --> 41:02.900
That is what we need.

41:10.100 --> 41:11.000
Thank you…

41:14.200 --> 41:15.900
For being…

41:18.100 --> 41:19.000
Thank you.

41:20.200 --> 41:22.642
I don't think
you're slipping, Denny.

41:25.000 --> 41:26.200
I really don't.

41:30.000 --> 41:31.600
Okay.

